# Git credentials for setup.sh / repo-add.sh (copy to .env — gitignored):
#   cp .env.example .env && chmod 600 .env
# Shell format: KEY=value, no spaces around '='.
# Only the variables for the providers declared in repos.yaml are needed;
# `local` repos and ssh URLs (git@...) use no token.

# ---------- GitHub (repos with provider: github) ----------
# Classic or fine-grained PAT with contents read permission.
# create at: github.com > Settings > Developer settings > Personal access tokens
#GITHUB_TOKEN=paste_your_token_here
# optional user (default: x-access-token, valid for PATs)
#GITHUB_USER=

# ---------- GitLab (repos with provider: gitlab) ----------
# PAT with read_repository scope (gitlab.com or self-hosted).
#GITLAB_TOKEN=paste_your_token_here
# optional user (default: oauth2, valid for PATs)
#GITLAB_USER=

# ---------- Bitbucket (repos with provider: bitbucket) ----------
# BITBUCKET_USER depends on the TYPE of token you use:
#   - App Password            -> your Bitbucket username   (e.g. my-user)
#     create at: bitbucket.org > Personal settings > App passwords
#     minimum permission: Repositories: Read (Write if you will push)
#   - Atlassian API token     -> your account email
#     create at: id.atlassian.com > Security > API tokens
#   - Repo/project/workspace Access Token -> x-token-auth
#     create at: Repository/Workspace settings > Access tokens
# NOTE - scoped API tokens (ATATT, ~190+ chars): the REST API accepts them
# with your email, but GIT requires the user x-bitbucket-api-token-auth.
# setup.sh applies it automatically; to force it manually uncomment:
#BITBUCKET_GIT_USER=x-bitbucket-api-token-auth
#BITBUCKET_USER=
#BITBUCKET_TOKEN=paste_your_token_here
